{{Expand Spanish|Idioma selk'nam|date=September 2013}}
{{Infobox language | name = Ona | nativename = Selk'nam | state = [[Argentina]] [[Chile]] | region = Patagonia, Tierra del Fuego. | ethnicity = [[Selk'nam people|Selk'nam]] | extinct = 1970s | ref = e19 | familycolor = American | fam1 = [[Chonan languages|Chonan]] | fam2 = Chon proper | fam3 = Island Chon | iso3 = ona | glotto = onaa1245 | glottorefname = Ona }}
'''Ona''' (Aona), also known as '''Selk'nam''' (Shelknam), is a language that is spoken by the [[Selk'nam people]] in [[Isla Grande de Tierra del Fuego]] in southernmost [[South America]].
Part of the [[Chonan languages]] of [[Patagonia]], Selk'nam is almost extinct, due both to the late 19th-century [[Selk'nam genocide]] by [[Spanish Argentines|European immigrants]], high fatalities due to disease and disruption of traditional society. One source states that the last fluent native speakers died in the 1980s,<ref name=Adelaar>Adelaar, Willem (2010). "South America". In Christopher (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=kFVthqmDs_kC ''Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger''], 3rd Edition. UNESCO. pp. 86-94.</ref>{{rp|92}} but another claims that two speakers had survived into 2014.<ref name=Berscia>Rojas, Luis (2014). A Heritage Reference Grammar of Selk'nam. Manuscript.</ref>
==History== The [[Selk'nam people]], also known as the '''Ona'', were an [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous people]] who inhabited the northeastern part of the archipelago of [[Tierra del Fuego]] for thousands of years before Europeans arrived. They were nomads known as "foot-people," as they did their hunting on land, rather than being seafarers.
The last full-blooded Selk'nam, [[Ángela Loij]], died in 1974. They were one of the last aboriginal groups in [[South America]] to be reached by Europeans. Their language, believed to be part of the [[Chonan languages|Chonan]] family, is considered extinct as the last speakers died in the 1980s.
== Phonology == Based on available data, Selk'nam seems to have had 3 vowels and 23 consonants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~saphon|title=SAPhon – South American Phonological Inventories|website=linguistics.berkeley.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-08-03}}</ref>
Selk'nam has three vowels: {{IPA|/a, ɪ, ʊ/}}. {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+Consonants ! rowspan="2" | ! colspan="2" |[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Dental consonant|Dental]] ! colspan="2" |[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! colspan="2" |[[Palato-alveolar consonant|Palato-alveolar]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! colspan="2" |[[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! colspan="2" |[[Uvular consonant|Uvular]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] |- ![[Stop consonant|Stop]] |{{IPA|p}} |{{IPA|pʼ}} | |{{IPA|t}} |{{IPA|tʼ}} | | | | |{{IPA|k}} |{{IPA|kʼ}} |{{IPA|q}} |{{IPA|qʼ}} |{{IPA|ʔ}} |- ![[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] | | | | | |{{IPA|t͡ʃ}} |{{IPA|t͡ʃʼ}} | | | | | | | |- ![[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | | |{{IPA|s̪}} |{{IPA|s}} | |{{IPA|ʃ}} | |{{IPA|ʂ}} | |{{IPA|x}} | | | |{{IPA|h}} |- ![[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |{{IPA|m}} | | |{{IPA|n}} | | | | | | | | | | |- ![[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | | |{{IPA|l}} | | | | |{{IPA|j}} |{{IPA|w}} | | | | |- ![[Flap consonant|Flap]] | | | |{{IPA|ɾ}} | | | | | | | | | | |}
==Grammar== The Ona language is an [[Object–verb–subject|object–verb–subject language]]. There are only two word classes in Selk'nam: nouns and verbs.<ref>{{cite book|last=Najlis|first=Elena|title=Lengua selknam|year=1973|publisher=Universidad de Salvador|location=Buenos Aires}}</ref>
